10\n| \"Gebt uns ruhig die Schuld (den Rest k\u00f6nnt ihr behalten)\"<sup>23</sup>\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|align=\"center\"|22\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n| \"Danke\"<sup>24</sup>\n|align=\"center\"|36<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gfk-entertainment.com/news/platz-eins-der-charts-linkin-park-sind-zurueck.html|title=GfK Entertainment - Platz eins der Charts: Linkin Park sind zur\u00fcck|publisher=}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|57\n|align=\"center\"|56\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n| \"25\"\n|align=\"center\"|15\n|align=\"center\"|53\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n| \"Und los\"<sup>25</sup>\n| align=\"center\"| 53\n| align=\"center\"| \u2013\n| align=\"center\"| 71\n|-\n| 2015\n| \"Name drauf\"<sup>26</sup><small>(feat. [[Seven (Swiss singer)|Seven]])</small>\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n|-\n| 2017\n| \"Endzeitstimmung\"<sup>27</sup>\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2018\n| \"Tunnel\"<sup>28</sup>\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n|-\n| \"[[Zusammen (song)|Zusammen]]\"<sup>29</sup><small>(feat. [[Clueso]])</small>\n| align=\"center\"| 2\n| align=\"center\"| 32<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://oe3.orf.at/charts/stories/oe3austriatop40/|title=\u00d63 Austria Top40: Single-Charts  - \u00d63 Charts|website=oe3.ORF.at}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 35\n|-\n| \"Hitisn\"\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n|-\n! colspan=7 style=\"font-size:85%\" bgcolor=#F8F8FF| Title translations:\n<ol start=1><li>\"Microphone Professor\"</ol>\n<ol start=2><li>\"Janitor Thomas D.\" (Thomas D.'s \"title\" of Hausmeister is also something of a play on words, as the literal meaning of the fragments Haus(\"house\") and Meister(\"master\") (alluding to house music) is also implied)</ol>\n<ol start=3><li>\"Her\" or \"This one over there\" <small>(\"Die\" describing a feminine [[German grammar#Grammar|grammatical gender]] implies the fact that the group is talking about a female person.)</small></ol>\n<ol start=4><li>\"Merry Celebration\" <small>(literally)</small>; \"Merry Christmas\" <small>(actual meaning)</small></ol>\n<ol start=5><li>\"Juice\"</ol>\n<ol start=6><li>\"Let the Sun come in\" <small>(literally)</small>; \"Let the sunshine in\" <small>(actual meaning)</small></ol>\n<ol start=7><li>\"Too Horny for this World\" <small>(literally)</small>; \"Too Hot for this World\" <small>(actual slang meaning)</small></ol>\n<ol start=8><li>\"Day at the ocean\" or \"Day at the seaside\"</ol>\n<ol start=9><li>\"She Is Gone\"</ol>\n<ol start=10><li>\"Popular\"</ol>\n<ol start=11><li>\"Only in your Head\"</ol>\n<ol start=12><li>\"Get Out\"</ol>\n<ol start=13><li>\"The Picnicker\"</ol>\n<ol start=14><li><small>(\"MfG\" is the official German abbreviation for \"Mit freundlichen Gr\u00fc\u00dfen\" which means \"With Best Regards\")</small></ol>\n<ol start=15><li><small>(\"Le\" is a masculine grammatical gender in [[French language]] and implies the fact that \"Smou\" is a male person.)</small></ol>\n<ol start=16><li>\"Buenos Dias Messiah!\" <small>(\"\u00a1Buenos D\u00edas!\" is the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] expression for \"Good Morning!\")</small></ol>\n<ol start=17><li><small>(Though being spelled \"[[Troy]]\", the song's lyrics make clear that the word (even in just the sentence where it is used) is meant to be a homophone to German \"treu\" which means \"loyal\" and \"faithful\". They, however, pronounce it rather like the English word.)</small></ol>\n<ol start=18><li>\"Summer Rain\"</ol>\n<ol start=19><li>\"Born\"</ol>\n<ol start=20><li>\"Reap What We Sow\"</ol>\n<ol start=21><li>\"Be Easy\" or \"Just Be\" <small>(literally)</small>; The chorus of the song is \"Everything could be so simple\"</ol>\n<ol start=22><li>\"IisIisIisI\" <small>(read as \"I is I is I is I\"; \"is\" is the nonstandard term for the 3. person form of the German verb \"sein\", which means \"to be\". Connected to \"Ich\" = \"I\" there is a volitional grammatical incorrectness)</small></ol>\n<ol start=23><li>\"Just put the blame on us or \"Give us only the guilt\"(but keep the rest for yourselves)\"</ol>\n<ol start=24><li>\"Thank you\"</ol>\n<ol start=25><li>\"And go\"</ol>\n<ol start=26><li>\"Marked with Name\"</ol>\n<ol start=27><li>\"Apocalyptic Mood\"</ol>\n<ol start=28><li>\"Tunnel\"</ol>\n<ol start=29><li>\"Together\"</ol>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Son Goku (band)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official|http://www.diefantastischenvier.de/ }} {{in lang|de}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070501094226/http://english.fourmusic.com/ Four Music]\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Die+Fantastischen+Vier Discography at [[Discogs]]]\n* [http://astore.amazon.de/fantastischen-vier-21 Fantastischen Vier Music Page]\n\n{{Die Fantastischen Vier}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fantastischen Vier, Die}}\n[[Category:Die Fantastischen Vier| ]]\n[[Category:German musical groups]]\n[[Category:German hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Stuttgart]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Die Fantastischen Vier\n| image               = FANTA 4.jpg\n| caption             = Die Fantastischen Vier in 1999\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Stuttgart]], [[Germany]]\n| genre               = [[German hip hop]], [[pop rap]]\n| years_active        = 1986 (1989) \u2013 present\n| label               = [[Four Music]], [[Sony BMG]]\n| website             = [http://www.diefantastischenvier.de/ Official website]\n| current_members     = [[Michael Beck (singer)|Michael Beck]]<br />[[Thomas D]]\u00fcrr<br />[[Smudo|Michael B. Schmidt]]<br />[[Andreas Rieke]]\n}}\n\n'''Die Fantastischen Vier''' ({{IPA-de|di\u02d0 fan\u02c8tast\u026a\u0283\u0259n \u02c8fi\u02d0\u0250\u032f}}, {{lang-en|The Fantastic Four}}), also known as '''Fanta 4''', is a [[German pop-rap]] group from [[Stuttgart]], [[Germany]], named after the German title of [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]]'s [[Fantastic Four]]. The members are [[Smudo|Smudo (Michael Bernd Schmidt)]], [[And.Ypsilon|And.Ypsilon (Andreas Rieke)]], [[Thomas D|Thomas D (Thomas D\u00fcrr)]], also dubbed \"''Hausmeister''\" (janitor), and [[Michael Beck (singer)|Dee Jot Hausmarke (Michi Beck)]]. They were, together with [[Advanced Chemistry]], among the first groups to rap in the German language.<ref name=autogenerated1>Brown, Timothy S. \u201c\u2018Keeping it Real\u2019 in a Different \u2018Hood: (African-) Americanization and Hip-hop in Germany.\u201d In The Vinyl Ain\u2019t Final: Hip Hop and the Globalization of Black Popular Culture, ed. by Dipannita Basu and Sidney J. Lemelle, 137-50. London</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Fanta heimspiel 09 02.jpg|thumb|Die Fantastischen Vier at their \"Heimspiel\" (\"Home Match\") gig in 2009.]]\n[[Image:Die Fantastischen 4.jpg|thumb|Thomas D, Smudo and And.Ypsilon at the [[Internationale Automobil-Ausstellung|IAA]] interviewed by [[Janin Reinhardt]].]]\n\nIn the middle of the 1980s, Rieke and Schmidt formed the ''Terminal Team'', D\u00fcrr and Beck joined in 1989. Under the new name ''Die Fantastischen Vier'' (literally: \"The Fantastic Four\"), they made German hip hop, or ''Deutschen [[Sprechgesang]]'' ''(German spoken-song)'' as they called it, popular in Germany. Although there were German hip-hop artists prior to them (such as [[Advanced Chemistry]] from [[Heidelberg]]) it was Die Fantastischen Vier who registered the first chart hit with their 1992 single \"Die da?!\" from the album ''[[4 Gewinnt]]'', hitting #2 in [[Germany]] and #1 in [[Austria]] and [[Switzerland]].\n\nAfter traveling to [[Los Angeles]] in the late 1980s, the group realized the lack of connection between the struggles of \"the poor Blacks in the United States and middle-class Whites in Germany,\"<ref name=autogenerated1 /> and made a conscious effort to move away from the typical and clich\u00e9 American gangster rap. The group never got involved with [[United States|US-American]] [[gangsta rap]] clich\u00e9s, reacting with tongue-in-cheek humor to verbal attacks of alleged German gangsta rappers. In the albums following ''4 Gewinnt'', the band matured and progressed to a more serious and philosophic style.\n\nThe band was extremely successful in the 1990s, when they released their hit single Die Da?! (Her?! The One Over There?!) in 1992. It was arguably the first German hip hop hit and also the breakthrough for Fanta 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxytunes.com/artist/die_fantastischen_vier|title=Yahoo|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the group's works, Thomas D, Hausmarke and Ypsilon also produced successful [[solo album]]s and the four had their own weekly show ''Die 4. Dimension'', named after their [[Die 4. Dimension|third album]], which aired on the German [[Pay television|pay TV]] channel [[Premiere (pay television network)|Premiere]] in 1993/1994.\n\nAt the 1996 [[Popkomm]] in [[Cologne]], Die Fantastischen Vier announced the establishment of their label, [[Four Music]]. Headquarters were in [[Stuttgart]], but were later moved to [[Kreuzberg|Berlin-Kreuzberg]].\n\nThree years later, the group's 7th album ''[[4:99]]'' was released on their own label, with 4 singles from the album following. After the #2 hit \"MfG\", three singles were released at the same time, a first in German music business. Each one can be associated with one of the rappers: \"Le Smou\" (''The Smou''; Smudo), \"Michi Beck in Hell\" (Michi Beck) and \"Buenos Dias Messias\" (''Good day, [[Messiah]]''; Thomas D).\n\nIn late September 2004, Die Fantastischen Vier released the album ''[[Viel]]'', the following tour being their most successful and best-attended to date.\n\nIn 2005, Fanta 4's first [[greatest hits]] album was published. It includes all singles, as well as several other songs and rare footage from the band's early days, when they were still called \"Terminal Team\" and rapped in English.\n[[File:Michael beck 1.jpg|thumb|Michael Beck (2010)]]\nOn 7 April 2007, the number-one album ''[[Fornika]]'' was released, preceded by the single \"Ernten was wir s\u00e4en\" ''(Reap what we sow)''.\n\nTheir song \"Ernten was wir s\u00e4en\" was released as a download for ''[[Guitar Hero III: Legends of Rock]]'' in December 2007 and was recently covered by [[Oomph!]].\n\nThey are also the German voices of the Penguins (Michael Beck as Skipper, Thomas D. as Kowalski, Andreas Rieke as Rico and Michael Bernd Schmidt as Private) in the ''Madagascar'' film series.\n\nIn 2010, ''[[F\u00fcr Dich Immer Noch Fanta Sie]]'' peaked again at number one of the German charts.\n\nThe 2014 release of the album ''[[Rekord (album)|Rekord]]'' marked the 25th anniversary of the band. It also topped the charts in Germany.\n\nIn 2018, the single \"[[Zusammen (song)|Zusammen]]\", featuring [[Clueso]], from the album ''[[Captain Fantastic (album)|Captain Fantastic]]'' was chosen as the official song for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] by German public broadcaster [[Das Erste]].\n\n== Discography ==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! colspan=\"3\"| Chart positions\n|-\n! [[GfK Entertainment Charts|Germany]]\n! [[Austria]]\n! [[Switzerland]]\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Jetzt geht's ab!]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 22\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|- \n| 1992\n| ''[[4 Gewinnt]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 3\n| align=\"center\"| 3\n| align=\"center\"| 3\n|- \n| 1993\n| ''[[Die 4. Dimension]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 14\n| align=\"center\"| 23\n| align=\"center\"| 27\n|- \n| 1994\n| ''[[Megavier]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 21\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|- \n| 1995\n| ''[[Lauschgift]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 2\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| align=\"center\"| 5\n|- \n| 1996\n| ''[[Live und direkt]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 17\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| 30\n|- \n| 1999\n| ''[[4:99]]''\n| align=\