pan=\"3\"| 2018\n| \"Tunnel\"<sup>28</sup>\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n|-\n| \"[[Zusammen (song)|Zusammen]]\"<sup>29</sup><small>(feat. [[Clueso]])</small>\n| align=\"center\"| 2\n| align=\"center\"| 32<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://oe3.orf.at/charts/stories/oe3austriatop40/|title=\u00d63 Austria Top40: Single-Charts  - \u00d63 Charts|website=oe3.ORF.at}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 35\n|-\n| \"Hitisn\"\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n|-\n! colspan=7 style=\"font-size:85%\" bgcolor=#F8F8FF| Title translations:\n<ol start=1><li>\"Microphone Professor\"</ol>\n<ol start=2><li>\"Janitor Thomas D.\" (Thomas D.'s \"title\" of Hausmeister is also something of a play on words, as the literal meaning of the fragments Haus(\"house\") and Meister(\"master\") (alluding to house music) is also implied)</ol>\n<ol start=3><li>\"Her\" or \"This one over there\" <small>(\"Die\" describing a feminine [[German grammar#Grammar|grammatical gender]] implies the fact that the group is talking about a female person.)</small></ol>\n<ol start=4><li>\"Merry Celebration\" <small>(literally)</small>; \"Merry Christmas\" <small>(actual meaning)</small></ol>\n<ol start=5><li>\"Juice\"</ol>\n<ol start=6><li>\"Let the Sun come in\" <small>(literally)</small>; \"Let the sunshine in\" <small>(actual meaning)</small></ol>\n<ol start=7><li>\"Too Horny for this World\" <small>(literally)</small>; \"Too Hot for this World\" <small>(actual slang meaning)</small></ol>\n<ol start=8><li>\"Day at the ocean\" or \"Day at the seaside\"</ol>\n<ol start=9><li>\"She Is Gone\"</ol>\n<ol start=10><li>\"Popular\"</ol>\n<ol start=11><li>\"Only in your Head\"</ol>\n<ol start=12><li>\"Get Out\"</ol>\n<ol start=13><li>\"The Picnicker\"</ol>\n<ol start=14><li><small>(\"MfG\" is the official German abbreviation for \"Mit freundlichen Gr\u00fc\u00dfen\" which means \"With Best Regards\")</small></ol>\n<ol start=15><li><small>(\"Le\" is a masculine grammatical gender in [[French language]] and implies the fact that \"Smou\" is a male person.)</small></ol>\n<ol start=16><li>\"Buenos Dias Messiah!\" <small>(\"\u00a1Buenos D\u00edas!\" is the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] expression for \"Good Morning!\")</small></ol>\n<ol start=17><li><small>(Though being spelled \"[[Troy]]\", the song's lyrics make clear that the word (even in just the sentence where it is used) is meant to be a homophone to German \"treu\" which means \"loyal\" and \"faithful\". They, however, pronounce it rather like the English word.)</small></ol>\n<ol start=18><li>\"Summer Rain\"</ol>\n<ol start=19><li>\"Born\"</ol>\n<ol start=20><li>\"Reap What We Sow\"</ol>\n<ol start=21><li>\"Be Easy\" or \"Just Be\" <small>(literally)</small>; The chorus of the song is \"Everything could be so simple\"</ol>\n<ol start=22><li>\"IisIisIisI\" <small>(read as \"I is I is I is I\"; \"is\" is the nonstandard term for the 3. person form of the German verb \"sein\", which means \"to be\". Connected to \"Ich\" = \"I\" there is a volitional grammatical incorrectness)</small></ol>\n<ol start=23><li>\"Just put the blame on us or \"Give us only the guilt\"(but keep the rest for yourselves)\"</ol>\n<ol start=24><li>\"Thank you\"</ol>\n<ol start=25><li>\"And go\"</ol>\n<ol start=26><li>\"Marked with Name\"</ol>\n<ol start=27><li>\"Apocalyptic Mood\"</ol>\n<ol start=28><li>\"Tunnel\"</ol>\n<ol start=29><li>\"Together\"</ol>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Son Goku (band)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official|http://www.diefantastischenvier.de/ }} {{in lang|de}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070501094226/http://english.fourmusic.com/ Four Music]\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Die+Fantastischen+Vier Discography at [[Discogs]]]\n* [http://astore.amazon.de/fantastischen-vier-21 Fantastischen Vier Music Page]\n\n{{Die Fantastischen Vier}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fantastischen Vier, Die}}\n[[Category:Die Fantastischen Vier| ]]\n[[Category:German musical groups]]\n[[Category:German hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Stuttgart]]\n", "name_user": "Wakuran", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Die_Fantastischen_Vier"}
{"title_page": "This City (Sam Fischer song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = This City\n| cover      = This_City_by_Sam_Fischer.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Sam Fischer]]\n| album      = Not a Hobby\n| released   = 18 January 2018 <br> 13 December 2019 <small>(re-release)</small>\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Media streaming|streaming]]\n| recorded   = 2017\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:14\n| label      = {{Flatlist|\n*[[RCA Records|RCA]]\n*[[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]]}}\n| writer     = {{Flatlist|\n* Sam Fischer\n* Jackson Morgan\n* [[James Michael Robbins]]}}\n| producer   = {{Flatlist|\n* Sam Fischer}}\n | prev_title = Smoke\n | prev_year  = 2018\n | next_title = Restless\n | next_year  = 2018\n| misc = \n{{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Sam Fischer]]\n| type       = singles\n| prev_title = Everybody Wants You\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| title = This City\n| year = 2019\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = }}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|s3IAHXP1dfs|\"This City\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''This City'''\" is a song by Australian recording artist [[Sam Fischer]]. The song was recorded in 2017 and was released in January 2018 as the third and final single on Fischer's debut EP ''Not a Hobby''.<ref name=\"amazon18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/This-City/dp/B0792P43S3|title=This City single by Sam Fischer|website=Amazon|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HDD\"/> Fisher said \"I wrote this with [[James Michael Robbins]] and Jackson Morgan on a day when I felt pretty damn defeated by [[Los Angeles|LA]]. Change is really hard, but so important. This is my experience, one that almost everyone goes through, hope it helps in some way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/samfischermusic/videos/this-city-is-out-everywhere-but-spotify-right-now-but-were-working-on-it-%EF%B8%8F%EF%B8%8Fi-wro/1535664703136839/|title=\"This City\" Is Out|website=[[Facebook]]|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nAfter signing with [[RCA Records]] in 2019, the song was re-released.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sportplaylists.com/sam-fischer-this-city |title= Australian singer-songwriter Sam Fischer drops 'This City' single |date=20 December 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> <ref name=\"iTunes\"/> \n\n==Background and composition==\nFischer wrote \"This City\" in 2016 and it was released in early 2018 where it was shared by people including [[Meghan Trainor]] and [[Lewis Capaldi]].<ref name=\"TMN\"/> In 2020 Fischer reflects saying \"The song got a lot of eyes on it, but it wasn't getting any love from anyone for a long time except for the fans. When I say anyone, I mean [[Spotify]], [[Apple Music|Apple]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]. But it was a fan-favourite.\"<ref name=\"TMN\"/>  \n\n18 months later, it was featured on [[TikTok]] and as Fischer says \"It changed everything for me\". The exposure lead to Fischer receiving a [[direct message|DM]] from [[RCA Records|RCA Records UK]] which lead to the signing.<ref name=\"TMN\">{{cite web|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/sam-fischer-interview/|title= Aussie hitmaker Sam Fischer talks isolation in LA & viral hit \"This City\"|website=The Music Network|date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HDD\">{{cite web|url=https://hitsdailydouble.com/the_bside&id=319859|title=Sam Fischer (Sony U.K./RCA)|website=Hits Daily Double|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listings==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Original<ref name=\"iTunes\"/>\n| title1  = This City\n| length1 = 3:14\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Luca Schreiner remix<ref name=\"Luca\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/this-city-luca-schreiner-remix-single/1495078031|title=This City Luca Schreiner remix- single |website=Apple Music|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| title1  = This City\n| note1   = [[Luca Schreiner]] remix\n| length1 = 2:56\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Acoustic<ref name=\"Acoustic\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/this-city-acoustic-single/1503376988|title=This City Acoustic- single |website=Apple Music|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| title1  = This City\n| note1   = Acoustic remix\n| length1 = 3:26\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Frank Walker remix<ref name=\"Frank\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/this-city-frank-walker-remix-single/1505596218|title=This City Frank Walker remix - single |website=Apple Music|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| title1  = This City\n| note1   = Frank Walker remix\n| length1 = 2:50\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australian Artists ([[ARIA Charts]])<ref name=\"6Apr20\">{{cite web|url=http://cdn.aria.com.au/pdfs/AA4A4D694AEC19A9A92DBBB0A4BC933A3AA7AFE3F5A26136BDF01C5998B90EB0/ARIA%20Australian%20Artist%20Singles%20Chart.pdf?seq=31|title=ARIA Australian Artist Singles Chart|publisher=[[ARIA]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 12\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 53\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| UK Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/57090/sam-fischer/|title=Sam Fischer {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 39\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! Region\n! Date\n! Format\n! Label\n! Version\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Various\n| 18 January 2018<ref name=\"amazon18\"/>\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n|{{Flatlist|\n*RI Entertainment}}\n| Original\n|-\n| 13 December 2019<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/this-city-single/1490897606|title=This City - single |website=Apple Music|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Digital download, [[Media streaming|streaming]]\n|{{Flatlist|\n*[[RCA Records|RCA]]\n*[[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music]]}}\n| Original (re-release)\n|-\n| Australia\n| 17 January 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/charts/issues/1272/1272-singles-to-radio/|title=Singles To Radio 17 January 2020|website=The Music Network|date=17 January 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| [[Contemporary hit radio]]\n| [[Sony Music Australia]]\n| Original \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| Various\n| 21 February 2020<ref name=\"Luca\"/>\n|rowspan=\"3\"| Digital download, streaming\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{Flatlist|\n*RCA\n*Sony Music}}\n| Luca Schreiner remix\n|-\n| 27 March 2020<ref name=\"Acoustic\"/>\n| Acoustic\n|-\n| 3 April 2020<ref name=\"Frank\"/>\n| Frank Walker remix\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2016 songs]]\n[[Category:2018 singles]]\n[[Category:2019 singles]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:Sony Music singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jimmy Robbins]]\n\n{{2010s-single-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = This City\n| cover      = This_City_by_Sam_Fischer.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Sam Fischer]]\n| album      = Not a Hobby\n| released   = 18 January 2018 <br> 13 December 2019 <small>(re-release)</small>\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Media streaming|streaming]]\n| recorded   = 2017\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:14\n| label      = {{Flatlist|\n*[[RCA Records|RCA]]\n*[[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]]}}\n| writer     = {{Flatlist|\n* Sam Fischer\n* Jackson Morgan\n* [[James Michael Robbins]]}}\n| producer   = {{Flatlist|\n* Sam Fischer}}\n | prev_title = Smoke\n | prev_year  = 2018\n | next_title = Restless\n | next_year  = 2018\n| misc = \n{{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Sam Fischer]]\n| type       = singles\n| prev_title = Everybody Wants You\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| title = This City\n| year = 2019\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = }}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|s3IAHXP1dfs|\"This City\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''This City'''\" is a song by Australian recording artist [[Sam Fischer]]. The song was recorded in 2017 and was released in January 2018 as the third and final single on Fischer's debut EP ''Not a Hobby''.<ref name=\"amazon18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/This-City/dp/B0792P43S3|title=This City single by Sam Fischer|website=Amazon|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HDD\"/> Fisher said \"I wrote this with [[James Michael Robbins]] and Jackson Morgan on a day when I felt pretty damn defeated by [[Los Angeles|LA]]. Change is really hard, but so important. This is my experience, one that almost everyone goes through, hope it helps in some way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/samfischermusic/videos/this-city-is-out-everywhere-but-spotify-right-now-but-were-working-on-it-%EF%B8%8F%EF%B8%8Fi-wro/1535664703136839/|title=\"This City\" Is Out|website=[[Facebook]]|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nAfter signing with [[RCA Records]] in 2019, the song was re-released.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sportplaylists.com/sam-fischer-this-city |title= Australian singer-songwriter Sam Fischer drops 'This City' single |date=20 December 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> <ref name=\"iTunes\"/> \n\n==Background and composition==\nFischer wrote \"This City\" in 2016 and it was released in early 2018 where it was shared by people including [[Meghan Trainor]] and [[Lewis Capaldi]].<ref name=\"TMN\"/> In 2020 Fischer reflects saying \"The song got a lot of eyes on it, but it wasn't getting any love from anyone for a long time except for the fans. When I say anyone, I mean [[Spotify]], [[Apple Music|Apple]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]. But it was a fan-favourite.\"<ref name=\"TMN\"/>  \n\n18 months later, it was featured on [[TikTok]] and as Fischer says \"It changed everything for me\". The exposure lead to Fischer receiving a [[direct message|DM]] from [[RCA Records|RCA Records UK]] which lead to the signing.<ref name=\"TMN\">{{cite web|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/sam-fischer-interview/|title= Aussie hitmaker Sam Fischer talks isolation in LA & viral hit \"This City\"|website=The Music Network|date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HDD\">{{cite web|url=https://hitsdailydouble.com/the_bside&id=319859|title=Sam Fischer (Sony U.K./RCA)|website=Hits Daily Double|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listings==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Original<ref name=\"iTunes\"/>\n| title1  = This City\n| length1 = 3:14\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Luca Schreiner remix<ref name=\"Luca\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/this-city-luca-schreiner-remix-single/1495078031|title=This City Luca Schreiner remix- single |website=Apple Music|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| title1  = This City\n| note1   = [[Luca Schreiner]] remix\n| length1 = 2:56\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Acoustic<ref name=\"Acoustic\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/this-city-acoustic-single/1503376988|title=This City Acoustic- single |website=Apple Music|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| title1  = This City\n| note1   = Acoustic remix\n| length1 = 3:26\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Frank Walker remix<ref name=\"Frank\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/this-city-frank-walker-remix-single/1505596218|title=This City Frank Walker remix - single |website=Apple Music|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| title1  = This City\n| note1   = Frank Walker remix\n| length1 = 2:50\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australian Artists ([[ARIA Charts]])<ref name=\"6Apr20\">{{cite web|url=http://cdn.aria.com.au/pdfs/AA4A4D694AEC19A9A92DBBB0A4BC933A3AA7AFE3F5A26136BDF01C5998B90EB0/ARIA%20Australian%20Artist%20Singles%20Chart.pdf?seq=31|title=ARIA Australian Artist Singles Chart|publisher=[[ARIA]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 12\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 53\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| UK Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/57090/sam-fischer/|title=Sam Fischer {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 46\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! Region\n! Date\n! Format\n! Label\n! Version\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Various\n| 18 January 2018<ref name=\"amazon18\"/>\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n|{{Flatlist|\n*RI Entertainment}}\n| Original\n|-\n| 13 December 2019<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/this-city-single/1490897606|title=This City - single |website=Apple Music|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Digital download, [[Media streaming|streaming]]\n|{{Flatlist|\n*[[RCA Records|RCA]]\n*[[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music]]}}\n| Original (re-release)\n|-\n| Australia\n| 17 January 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/charts/issues/1272/1272-singles-to-radio/|title=Singles To Radio 17 January 2020|website=The Music Network|date=17 January 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| [[Contemporary hit radio]]\n| [[Sony Music Australia]]\n| Original \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| Various\n| 21 February 2020<ref name=\"Luca\"/>\n|rowspan=\"3\"| Digital download, streaming\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{Flatlist|\n*RCA\n*Sony Music}}\n| Luca Schreiner remix\n|-\n| 27 March 2020<ref name=\"Acoustic\"/>\n| Acoustic\n|-\n| 3 April 2020<ref name=\"Frank\"/>\n| Frank Walker remix\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2016 songs]]\n[[Category:2018 singles]]\n[[Category:2019 singles]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:Sony Music singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jimmy Robbins]]\n\n{{2010s-single-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/This_City_(Sam_Fischer_song)"}
{"title_page": "Loop Service", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|5.6|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|5.6|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] in downtown. After several years of planning, the city council adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in 2003. Upon its inaugural service in 2012, the Loop Service was known as the '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line'''). It initially ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Pearl District. It was re-branded to its current name upon the opening of Tilikum Crossing bridge in 2015.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line on the east side between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]] as proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane decks rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weidler avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weidler alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the OMSI\u2013Oregon Convention Center proposal along this planned bridge instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=[[Portland Bureau of Transportation|Portland Office of Transportation]] |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a westside\u2013eastside loop project that ran from the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]] through the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref> In 2008, a locally preferred alternative was selected for the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail project that included a new river crossing between the South Waterfron and OMSI;<ref name=oreg-2008may2>{{cite news |last=Mortenson |first=Eric |date=May 2, 2008 |title=Panel realigns route of new light-rail span |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> this led to a decision to extend the first phase of the eastside streetcar segment up to OMSI until the new bridge could be completed, after which the streetcar would cross the bridge back to the west side and thus form a complete loop.<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/transportation/article/408420 |title=Portland Streetcar Loop Development Strategy |publisher=Portland Office of Transportation |date=April 14, 2008 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|1}}<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2014/04/18/070908_portland_streetcar_loop_environmental_assessment_FONSI.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Loop environmental assessment: Finding of no significant impact |publisher=Metro |date=July 9, 2008 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2}}\n\n===Funding and construction===\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006 followed by the city council in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The total cost of the phase one project was $148.8{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148800000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including the cost to purchase additional vehicles.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\">{{cite report |url=https://www.transit.dot.gov/sites/fta.dot.gov/files/docs/funding/grant-programs/capital-investments/115401/2016-oregon-portland-streetcar-loop-project.pdf |title=Streetcar Loop Project Before-and-After Study (2016) |publisher=[[Federal Transit Administration]] |date=2016 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|19}} Just over half would be paid for with federal funds.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the locally matched financing.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland. This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was the largest and final component of the financing plan and meant the project could proceed with construction.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Streetcar 10T3 prototype for Portland.jpg|thumb|left|Unveiling of the United Streetcar 10T3 prototype in July 2009]]\n\nIn 2005, the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] approved a spending bill that included $4{{nbsp}}million for a locally produced streetcar vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |last=Hamilton |first=Don |title=Iron firm forges streetcar desire |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 5, 2005 |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331125621/https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |archive-date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> That money went to [[Oregon Iron Works]], which created the subsidiary [[United Streetcar]] upon receiving the contract to build new streetcars for the Portland Streetcar.<ref name=\"streetcarcontract\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Oregon Iron Works gets contract for streetcar |date=January 26, 2007 |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |url=https://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/01/22/daily45.html |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> In May 2009, United Streetcar delivered its first prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension.<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009. The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's general contractor and actual construction began the following year.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Across the alignment, crews laid tracks in three- to four-block increments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to all traffic to be renovated from July 19 to September 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> To maintain the existing weight of the bridge (this was necessary to allow the bridge to continue lifting its spans) and simultaneously add tracks, lighter fiber-reinforced concrete replaced the deck.<ref name=\"streetcar work\">{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Joseph |title=Streetcar work shutting down Broadway Bridge |date=July 5, 2010 <!--(July 4 online edition)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=A10 |url=https://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2010/07/streetcar_work_shuts_broadway.html |accessdate=November 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wrap-up-broadway\">{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/02/18/streetcar-work-almost-finished-on-broadway-bridge/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Streetcar work wraps up on Broadway Bridge |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In the Pearl District, sections of what had been two two-way streets\u2014Northwest Lovejoy and Northwest Northrup\u2014were converted into one-way streets following the addition of rails. Work completed in this district upon the reopening of the Lovejoy ramp on the west end of the Broadway Bridge in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/11/05/pearl-streets-reopen-with-changed-traffic-patterns/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Pearl streets reopen with changed traffic patterns |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=November 5, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In Southeast Portland, crews built a {{convert|425|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} bridge that carried the streetcar to OMSI, the project's eastern terminus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/12/22/portland-streetcar-flyover-bridge-near-omsi/ |last=Carter |first=Dan |title=Portland Streetcar flyover bridge near OMSI |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=December 22, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barber Block sunlit with streetcar, 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Car 015 in front of the [[Barber Block]] on Southeast Grand Avenue in 2012]] \n\nIn July 2011, the city council agreed to contractual changes that reduced the number of streetcars on order from six to five.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/07/20/eastside-streetcar-loop-will-be-delayed-number-of-cars-reduced/ |last=Webber |first=Angela |title=Eastside streetcar loop will be delayed, number of cars reduced |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> United Streetcar had depended on [[Czech Republic|Czech]] firm [[\u0160koda Transportation|\u0160koda]], which built the system's first streetcars, to build the new streetcars' propulsion system but these failed acceptance testing. Portland officials opted instead to source the propulsion system from [[Wisconsin]]-based [[Rockwell Automation]], but the design was still being developed at the time. They then pursued [[Austria]]n manufacturer Elin to produce a propulsion system for the prototype while they awaited Rockwell. Changes to the propulsion system necessitated changes to the streetcar design in order for the streetcar to accommodate a different form factor; this ultimately delayed the project and raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Opening and extension===\n\nThe {{convert|3.3|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} streetcar extension opened on September 22, 2012, after a five-month-long delay.<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Its inaugural service, branded the Central Loop Line (abbreviated as CL Line), ran {{convert|4.4|mi|km}} total from the NS Line tracks at Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to the Pearl District, then on the new tracks from the Broadway Bridge to OMSI in Southeast Portland.<ref name=\"PS-History\"/> Service along the eastside segment initially operated with frequencies of 18 minutes instead of an originally planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by TriMet and the City of Portland, as well as delays in streetcar delivery from United Streetcar.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref> The first car finally arrived in January 2013 and entered service on June 11, 2013.<ref name=\"oreg-2013jun12\">{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=Brad|title=New streetcar rolls out in Portland<!--(print-edition headline)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 12, 2013 |page=B1 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2013/06/after_repeated_delays_portland.html |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> Fares were $1 upon opening due to TriMet's elimination of the [[Fareless Square|Free Rail Zone]].<ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces 'Central Loop' Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> Approximately 3,200 riders per weekday used the line during the first two weeks of service.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2012/10/31/eastside-streetcar-carrying-the-wait.html |last=Giegerich |first=Andy |title=Eastside streetcar: Carrying the wait |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=October 31, 2012 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:A Lloyd via Peral (21612375879).jpg|thumb|left|An A Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015]]\n\nThe second phase of the Eastside Loop project, referred to as \"Close the Loop\", extended the CL Line from OMSI to the NS Line tracks on Southwest Moody Avenue in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]]. This phase of the project had awaited the construction of a new bridge for the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail project. That bridge, later named [[Tilikum Crossing]], began construction in 2012 and completed in 2015.\n\nOn August 30, 2015, service was extended {{convert|0.9|mi|km}} on the west side from Southwest 10th and Market streets along existing NS Line tracks south to Southwest Moody and Meade streets in the South Waterfront.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\"/>{{rp|19}} A new temporary schedule eliminated the name CL Line in favor of two separate routes: A Loop and B Loop. Streetcars began operating across the newly built [[Tilikum Crossing]], but without carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional \"pre-revenue service\" phase.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015,<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2018/12/07/RTP-Appendix_G_CTP_20160614.pdf |title=2018 Regional Transportation Plan: Coordinated transportation plan for seniors and people with disabilities |publisher=[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] |date=December 6, 2018 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2\u201313}} when the {{convert|1720|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} Tilikum Crossing opened to the public and began permitting streetcars to carry passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref name=\"tilikum-factsheet-2014\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/Fact-sheets-timelines/TC_2Page_June2014.pdf |title=Tilikum Crossing, Bridge of the People, brings new connections and new options in 2015 |publisher=TriMet |date=June 2014 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Route==\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|A B Loop streetcar crossing the Broadway Bridge in 2016]]\n\nThe Loop Service forms a {{convert|5.6|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[circle route]] between downtown Portland and the Central Eastside.<ref>{{cite map |url=https://www.transitmap.net/portland-streetcar-2015/ |title=Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=2015 |via=transitmap.net}}</ref> A majority of each route runs on single-track. From their original endpoint on Southwest Market Street, the A and B Loops travel northbound through downtown Portland to the Pearl District along NS Line tracks on 10th and 11th avenues.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+10th+%26+Clay/@45.5150904,-122.6838684,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a07f9361b:0x48d11b9676b62d09!8m2!3d45.5144961!4d-122.6849739 |title=SW 10th & Clay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+11th+%26+Clay/@45.5152692,-122.6853204,18z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a1bc20dab:0x5353b61f171ae97b!8m2!3d45.5151856!4d-122.6860428 |title=SW 11th & Clay |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The services meet at the intersection of Northwest 10th and Lovejoy where they proceed east towards the Broadway Bridge using the Eastside Loop extension tracks.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NW+9th+%26+Lovejoy/@45.5300511,-122.6789145,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x549509fe395af473:0x1f39de6a4894f631!8m2!3d45.5300534!4d-122.6806308 |title=NW 9th & Lovejoy |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> After crossing the Willamette River on this bridge, the tracks again split, with the A Loop tracks continuing east on Weidler Street and the B Loop tracks on Broadway Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/N+Weidler+%26+Ross/@45.5339555,-122.6694082,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523bc453bf:0xdf7d65ef2959f0dc!8m2!3d45.5344683!4d-122.6694356 |title=N Weidler & Ross |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Broadway+%26+Ross+(Streetcar)/@45.5337533,-122.6705135,17.04z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523a89db6d:0x734a73024c507be4!8m2!3d45.53445!4d-122.6695217 |title=NE Broadway & Ross (Streetcar) |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The B Loop turns right on Northeast Grand Avenue and proceeds south through to OMSI.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Grand+%26+Broadway/@45.533741,-122.6611424,17.83z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a74cee1672d9:0x4eb3a0bcd277cf43!8m2!3d45.5347981!4d-122.6605477 |title=NE Grand & Broadway |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right onto Northeast 7th Avenue,<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Halsey+Southbound/@45.5318626,-122.6610966,17.29z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b333c19a1d:0x22d53ea9dc86a0cb!8m2!3d45.5334298!4d-122.6585944 |title=NE 7th & Halsey Southbound |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> turns left onto Northeast Oregon street, turns left again onto Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard in front of the Oregon Convention Center, and heads south.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Oregon+%26+Grand/@45.5286027,-122.6627257,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0adec0981b1:0xa2326856bed21290!8m2!3d45.5286869!4d-122.6604364 |title=NE Oregon & Grand |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Both tracks intersect MAX Light Rail tracks on Holladay Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Holladay/@45.5299588,-122.6609103,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b25eeab5ef:0xa0465a316dd28817!8m2!3d45.5308073!4d-122.6586092 |title=NE 7th & Holladay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The lines rejoin and enter an overpass at Southeast Harrison Street, which carries them to OMSI.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SE+Water%2FOMSI+(Streetcar)/@45.5079612,-122.6631697,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a7236697d75:0x40bba82a7a827677!8m2!3d45.5069508!4d-122.663364 |title=SE Water/OMSI (Streetcar) |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom OMSI, the A and B Loops approach Tilikum Crossing and cross the river back to the west side. They re-merge with the NS Line alignment on Southwest Moody Avenue. The tracks turn left onto Southwest River Parkway, which turns into Southwest Harrison Street. They turn right on Southwest 4th Street, then left on Southwest Montgomery Street, and split again at Southwest 5th Avenue. The A Loop crosses PSU's [[Urban Plaza]] diagonally for Southwest Mill Street and the B Loop turns right on Southwest 5th Avenue.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/PSU+Urban+Center/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a112fe8f51f:0xb93dc6c9ec4eada!8m2!3d45.5122199!4d-122.6820778 |title=PSU Urban Center |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+5th+%26+Montgomery/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a11485235eb:0x54962f4617846156!8m2!3d45.5117905!4d-122.6812866 |title=SW 5th & Montgomery |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right at Southwest 10th Avenue and returns to the intersection of Southwest 10th and Market. The B Loop turns left onto Southwest Market Street and proceeds left until it returns to Southwest 11th and Market. \n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, 24 of which are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at ten stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Library and Galleria stations]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Central Library (Portland, Oregon)|Central Library]]\n|-\n| Art Museum\n| Southwest 11th & Jefferson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland Art Museum]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Clay\n| Southwest 11th & Clay\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Southwest Park & Mill\n| Southwest Park & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[South Park Blocks]]\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Southwest 5th & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| PSU Urban Center\n| Southwest 5th & Montgomery\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[PSU Urban Center stations]]: [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest 3rd & Harrison\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Harrison Street\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest River Parkway & Moody\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Moody & Meade\n| align=\"center\" | [[South Waterfront]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Health and Sciences University|OHSU]] Robertson Life Sciences Building, [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | OMSI\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[OMSI/Southeast Water station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]], [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Mill\n| Southeast Grand & Mill\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Hawthorne\n| Southeast Grand & Hawthorne\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Taylor\n| Southeast Grand & Taylor\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Morrison\n| Southeast Grand & Morrison\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Stark\n| Southeast Grand & Stark\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast MLK & East Burnside\n| Southeast Grand & East Burnside\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Oregon Convention Center\n| Northeast Grand & Hoyt\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Convention Center station (TriMet)|Convention Center station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Convention Center]]\n|-\n| Northeast Oregon & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Holladay\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Holladay\n| Northeast Grand & Multnomah\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Northeast 7th Avenue station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Halsey\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Broadway\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & 2nd\n| Northeast Broadway & 2nd\n| \u2014\n|-\n| North Weidler & Ross\n| North Broadway & Ross\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Service==\n\nThe Loop Service operates from 5:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on weekdays, from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on Saturdays, and from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 10:30&nbsp;p.m. on Sundays. Frequencies in each direction range from 15 minutes between 10:00&nbsp;a.m. and 7:00&nbsp;pm on weekdays and Saturdays to 20 minutes on Sundays.<ref name=\"a-loop-schedules\">A Loop schedules:\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Weekday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Weekday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Saturday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Saturday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Sunday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Sunday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"b-loop-schedules\">B Loop schedules:\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Weekday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Weekday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Saturday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Saturday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Sunday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Sunday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 Portland Streetcar Loop Service]\n*[http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 Portland Streetcar schedule]\n\n{{Portland Transit}}\n{{Streetcars Portland Oregon}}\n{{Portal bar|Oregon|Trains|Transport}}\n\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2012]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:TriMet]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|5.6|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|5.6|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] in downtown. After several years of planning, the city council adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in 2003. Upon its inaugural service in 2012, the Loop Service was known as the '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line'''). It initially ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Pearl District. It was re-branded to its current name upon the opening of Tilikum Crossing bridge in 2015.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line on the east side between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]] as proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane decks rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weidler avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weidler alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the OMSI\u2013Oregon Convention Center proposal along this planned bridge instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=[[Portland Bureau of Transportation|Portland Office of Transportation]] |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a westside\u2013eastside loop project that ran from the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]] through the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref> In 2008, a locally preferred alternative was selected for the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail project that included a new river crossing between the South Waterfron and OMSI;<ref name=oreg-2008may2>{{cite news |last=Mortenson |first=Eric |date=May 2, 2008 |title=Panel realigns route of new light-rail span |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> this led to a decision to extend the first phase of the eastside streetcar segment up to OMSI until the new bridge could be completed, after which the streetcar would cross the bridge back to the west side and thus form a complete loop.<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/transportation/article/408420 |title=Portland Streetcar Loop Development Strategy |publisher=Portland Office of Transportation |date=April 14, 2008 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|1}}<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2014/04/18/070908_portland_streetcar_loop_environmental_assessment_FONSI.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Loop environmental assessment: Finding of no significant impact |publisher=Metro |date=July 9, 2008 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2}}\n\n===Funding and construction===\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006 followed by the city council in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The total cost of the phase one project was $148.8{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148800000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including the cost to purchase additional vehicles.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\">{{cite report |url=https://www.transit.dot.gov/sites/fta.dot.gov/files/docs/funding/grant-programs/capital-investments/115401/2016-oregon-portland-streetcar-loop-project.pdf |title=Streetcar Loop Project Before-and-After Study (2016) |publisher=[[Federal Transit Administration]] |date=2016 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|19}} Just over half would be paid for with federal funds.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the locally matched financing.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland. This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was the largest and final component of the financing plan and meant the project could proceed with construction.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Streetcar 10T3 prototype for Portland.jpg|thumb|left|Unveiling of the United Streetcar 10T3 prototype in July 2009]]\n\nIn 2005, the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] approved a spending bill that included $4{{nbsp}}million for a locally produced streetcar vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |last=Hamilton |first=Don |title=Iron firm forges streetcar desire |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 5, 2005 |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331125621/https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |archive-date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> That money went to [[Oregon Iron Works]], which created the subsidiary [[United Streetcar]] upon receiving the contract to build new streetcars for the Portland Streetcar.<ref name=\"streetcarcontract\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Oregon Iron Works gets contract for streetcar |date=January 26, 2007 |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |url=https://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/01/22/daily45.html |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> In May 2009, United Streetcar delivered its first prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension.<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009. The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's general contractor and actual construction began the following year.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Across the alignment, crews laid tracks in three- to four-block increments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to all traffic to be renovated from July 19 to September 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> To maintain the existing weight of the bridge (this was necessary to allow the bridge to continue lifting its spans) and simultaneously add tracks, lighter fiber-reinforced concrete replaced the deck.<ref name=\"streetcar work\">{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Joseph |title=Streetcar work shutting down Broadway Bridge |date=July 5, 2010 <!--(July 4 online edition)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=A10 |url=https://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2010/07/streetcar_work_shuts_broadway.html |accessdate=November 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wrap-up-broadway\">{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/02/18/streetcar-work-almost-finished-on-broadway-bridge/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Streetcar work wraps up on Broadway Bridge |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In the Pearl District, sections of what had been two two-way streets\u2014Northwest Lovejoy and Northwest Northrup\u2014were converted into one-way streets following the addition of rails. Work completed in this district upon the reopening of the Lovejoy ramp on the west end of the Broadway Bridge in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/11/05/pearl-streets-reopen-with-changed-traffic-patterns/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Pearl streets reopen with changed traffic patterns |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=November 5, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In Southeast Portland, crews built a {{convert|425|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} bridge that carried the streetcar to OMSI, the project's eastern terminus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/12/22/portland-streetcar-flyover-bridge-near-omsi/ |last=Carter |first=Dan |title=Portland Streetcar flyover bridge near OMSI |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=December 22, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barber Block sunlit with streetcar, 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Car 015 in front of the [[Barber Block]] on Southeast Grand Avenue in 2012]] \n\nIn July 2011, the city council agreed to contractual changes that reduced the number of streetcars on order from six to five.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/07/20/eastside-streetcar-loop-will-be-delayed-number-of-cars-reduced/ |last=Webber |first=Angela |title=Eastside streetcar loop will be delayed, number of cars reduced |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> United Streetcar had depended on [[Czech Republic|Czech]] firm [[\u0160koda Transportation|\u0160koda]], which built the system's first streetcars, to build the new streetcars' propulsion system but these failed acceptance testing. Portland officials opted instead to source the propulsion system from [[Wisconsin]]-based [[Rockwell Automation]], but the design was still being developed at the time. They then pursued [[Austria]]n manufacturer Elin to produce a propulsion system for the prototype while they awaited Rockwell. Changes to the propulsion system necessitated changes to the streetcar design in order for the streetcar to accommodate a different form factor; this ultimately delayed the project and raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Opening and extension===\n\nThe {{convert|3.3|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} streetcar extension opened on September 22, 2012, after a five-month-long delay.<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Its inaugural service, branded the Central Loop Line (abbreviated as CL Line), ran {{convert|4.4|mi|km}} total from the NS Line tracks at Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to the Pearl District, then on the new tracks from the Broadway Bridge to OMSI in Southeast Portland.<ref name=\"PS-History\"/> Service along the eastside segment initially operated with frequencies of 18 minutes instead of an originally planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by TriMet and the City of Portland, as well as delays in streetcar delivery from United Streetcar.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref> The first car finally arrived in January 2013 and entered service on June 11, 2013.<ref name=\"oreg-2013jun12\">{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=Brad|title=New streetcar rolls out in Portland<!--(print-edition headline)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 12, 2013 |page=B1 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2013/06/after_repeated_delays_portland.html |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> Fares were $1 upon opening due to TriMet's elimination of the [[Fareless Square|Free Rail Zone]].<ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces 'Central Loop' Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> Approximately 3,200 riders per weekday used the line during the first two weeks of service.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2012/10/31/eastside-streetcar-carrying-the-wait.html |last=Giegerich |first=Andy |title=Eastside streetcar: Carrying the wait |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=October 31, 2012 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:A Lloyd via Peral (21612375879).jpg|thumb|left|An A Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015]]\n\nThe second phase of the Eastside Loop project, referred to as \"Close the Loop\", extended the CL Line from OMSI to the NS Line tracks on Southwest Moody Avenue in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]]. This phase of the project had awaited the construction of a new bridge for the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail project. The bridge, later named [[Tilikum Crossing]], began construction in 2012 and completed in 2015.\n\nOn August 30, 2015, service was extended {{convert|0.9|mi|km}} on the west side from Southwest 10th and Market streets along existing NS Line tracks south to Southwest Moody and Meade streets in the South Waterfront.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\"/>{{rp|19}} A new temporary schedule eliminated the name CL Line in favor of two separate routes: A Loop and B Loop. Streetcars began operating across the newly built [[Tilikum Crossing]], but without carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional \"pre-revenue service\" phase.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015,<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2018/12/07/RTP-Appendix_G_CTP_20160614.pdf |title=2018 Regional Transportation Plan: Coordinated transportation plan for seniors and people with disabilities |publisher=[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] |date=December 6, 2018 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2\u201313}} when the {{convert|1720|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} Tilikum Crossing opened to the public and began permitting streetcars to carry passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref name=\"tilikum-factsheet-2014\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/Fact-sheets-timelines/TC_2Page_June2014.pdf |title=Tilikum Crossing, Bridge of the People, brings new connections and new options in 2015 |publisher=TriMet |date=June 2014 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Route==\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|A B Loop streetcar crossing the Broadway Bridge in 2016]]\n\nThe Loop Service forms a {{convert|5.6|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[circle route]] between downtown Portland and the Central Eastside.<ref>{{cite map |url=https://www.transitmap.net/portland-streetcar-2015/ |title=Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=2015 |via=transitmap.net}}</ref> A majority of each route runs on single-track. From their original endpoint on Southwest Market Street, the A and B Loops travel northbound through downtown Portland to the Pearl District along NS Line tracks on 10th and 11th avenues.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+10th+%26+Clay/@45.5150904,-122.6838684,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a07f9361b:0x48d11b9676b62d09!8m2!3d45.5144961!4d-122.6849739 |title=SW 10th & Clay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+11th+%26+Clay/@45.5152692,-122.6853204,18z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a1bc20dab:0x5353b61f171ae97b!8m2!3d45.5151856!4d-122.6860428 |title=SW 11th & Clay |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The services meet at the intersection of Northwest 10th and Lovejoy where they proceed east towards the Broadway Bridge using the Eastside Loop extension tracks.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NW+9th+%26+Lovejoy/@45.5300511,-122.6789145,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x549509fe395af473:0x1f39de6a4894f631!8m2!3d45.5300534!4d-122.6806308 |title=NW 9th & Lovejoy |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> After crossing the Willamette River on this bridge, the tracks again split, with the A Loop tracks continuing east on Weidler Street and the B Loop tracks on Broadway Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/N+Weidler+%26+Ross/@45.5339555,-122.6694082,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523bc453bf:0xdf7d65ef2959f0dc!8m2!3d45.5344683!4d-122.6694356 |title=N Weidler & Ross |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Broadway+%26+Ross+(Streetcar)/@45.5337533,-122.6705135,17.04z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523a89db6d:0x734a73024c507be4!8m2!3d45.53445!4d-122.6695217 |title=NE Broadway & Ross (Streetcar) |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The B Loop turns right on Northeast Grand Avenue and proceeds south through to OMSI.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Grand+%26+Broadway/@45.533741,-122.6611424,17.83z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a74cee1672d9:0x4eb3a0bcd277cf43!8m2!3d45.5347981!4d-122.6605477 |title=NE Grand & Broadway |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right onto Northeast 7th Avenue,<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Halsey+Southbound/@45.5318626,-122.6610966,17.29z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b333c19a1d:0x22d53ea9dc86a0cb!8m2!3d45.5334298!4d-122.6585944 |title=NE 7th & Halsey Southbound |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> turns left onto Northeast Oregon street, turns left again onto Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard in front of the Oregon Convention Center, and heads south.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Oregon+%26+Grand/@45.5286027,-122.6627257,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0adec0981b1:0xa2326856bed21290!8m2!3d45.5286869!4d-122.6604364 |title=NE Oregon & Grand |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Both tracks intersect MAX Light Rail tracks on Holladay Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Holladay/@45.5299588,-122.6609103,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b25eeab5ef:0xa0465a316dd28817!8m2!3d45.5308073!4d-122.6586092 |title=NE 7th & Holladay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The lines rejoin and enter an overpass at Southeast Harrison Street, which carries them to OMSI.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SE+Water%2FOMSI+(Streetcar)/@45.5079612,-122.6631697,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a7236697d75:0x40bba82a7a827677!8m2!3d45.5069508!4d-122.663364 |title=SE Water/OMSI (Streetcar) |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom OMSI, the A and B Loops approach Tilikum Crossing and cross the river back to the west side. They re-merge with the NS Line alignment on Southwest Moody Avenue. The tracks turn left onto Southwest River Parkway, which turns into Southwest Harrison Street. They turn right on Southwest 4th Street, then left on Southwest Montgomery Street, and split again at Southwest 5th Avenue. The A Loop crosses PSU's [[Urban Plaza]] diagonally for Southwest Mill Street and the B Loop turns right on Southwest 5th Avenue.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/PSU+Urban+Center/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a112fe8f51f:0xb93dc6c9ec4eada!8m2!3d45.5122199!4d-122.6820778 |title=PSU Urban Center |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+5th+%26+Montgomery/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a11485235eb:0x54962f4617846156!8m2!3d45.5117905!4d-122.6812866 |title=SW 5th & Montgomery |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right at Southwest 10th Avenue and returns to the intersection of Southwest 10th and Market. The B Loop turns left onto Southwest Market Street and proceeds left until it returns to Southwest 11th and Market. \n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, 24 of which are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at ten stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Library and Galleria stations]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Central Library (Portland, Oregon)|Central Library]]\n|-\n| Art Museum\n| Southwest 11th & Jefferson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland Art Museum]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Clay\n| Southwest 11th & Clay\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Southwest Park & Mill\n| Southwest Park & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[South Park Blocks]]\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Southwest 5th & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| PSU Urban Center\n| Southwest 5th & Montgomery\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[PSU Urban Center stations]]: [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest 3rd & Harrison\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Harrison Street\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest River Parkway & Moody\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Moody & Meade\n| align=\"center\" | [[South Waterfront]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Health and Sciences University|OHSU]] Robertson Life Sciences Building, [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | OMSI\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[OMSI/Southeast Water station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]], [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Mill\n| Southeast Grand & Mill\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Hawthorne\n| Southeast Grand & Hawthorne\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Taylor\n| Southeast Grand & Taylor\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Morrison\n| Southeast Grand & Morrison\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Stark\n| Southeast Grand & Stark\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast MLK & East Burnside\n| Southeast Grand & East Burnside\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Oregon Convention Center\n| Northeast Grand & Hoyt\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Convention Center station (TriMet)|Convention Center station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Convention Center]]\n|-\n| Northeast Oregon & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Holladay\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Holladay\n| Northeast Grand & Multnomah\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Northeast 7th Avenue station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Halsey\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Broadway\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & 2nd\n| Northeast Broadway & 2nd\n| \u2014\n|-\n| North Weidler & Ross\n| North Broadway & Ross\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Service==\n\nThe Loop Service operates from 5:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on weekdays, from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on Saturdays, and from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 10:30&nbsp;p.m. on Sundays. Frequencies in each direction range from 15 minutes between 10:00&nbsp;a.m. and 7:00&nbsp;pm on weekdays and Saturdays to 20 minutes on Sundays.<ref name=\"a-loop-schedules\">A Loop schedules:\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Weekday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Weekday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Saturday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Saturday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Sunday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Sunday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"b-loop-schedules\">B Loop schedules:\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Weekday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Weekday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Saturday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Saturday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Sunday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Sunday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 Portland Streetcar Loop Service]\n*[http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 Portland Streetcar schedule]\n\n{{Portland Transit}}\n{{Streetcars Portland Oregon}}\n{{Portal bar|Oregon|Trains|Transport}}\n\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2012]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:TriMet]]\n", "name_user": "Truflip99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOpening and extension:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loop_Service"}
